  "slug": "cheese-scones-cheddar",
  "title": "Cheese scones",
  "subtitle": "Cheddar-sharp savoury scones",
  "excerpt": "Savoury scones built on the same quick method as the sweet version: cold butter rubbed into flour, brought together with cold milk and a generous amount of mature cheddar. Sharp, golden, and best eaten warm.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: the standard scone method. Florence White, Good Things in England (1932): the cheddar cheese scone as a specifically British savoury bake, distinct from the sweet afternoon-tea version.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The cheese scone exists to be eaten warm, ideally with butter. The cheese should be mature cheddar, sharp, with enough acid to cut through the butter fat in the dough. Mild cheddar disappears into the background. Use at least 140 g of cheese and grate it coarsely so there are visible threads in the crumb and on the top.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "ingredientsList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "ingredientsGroup",
            "attrs": {
              "title": null
            },
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "ingredient",
                "attrs": {
                  "slug": "self-raising-flour",
                  "unit": "g",
                  "prepNote": null,
                  "quantity": 450,
                  "isOptional": false
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "ingredient",
                "attrs": {
                  "slug": "baking-powder",
                  "unit": "tsp",
                  "prepNote": null,
                  "quantity": 1,
                  "isOptional": false
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "ingredient",
                "attrs": {
                  "slug": "fine-sea-salt",
